    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "213b3b68_52c38e45",
        "filename": "golden/puppeteer-tests/docker/Dockerfile",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 14,
      "author": {
        "id": 10009
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-11-07T21:31:44Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yes, but only if we use the Chromium version that\u0027s bundled with Puppeteer.\n\nFYI, I\u0027ve modeled my code after lottiecap, which skips the Puppeteer Chromium download[1], downloads its own Chrome version[2] and tells Puppeteer to use that instead of the bundled one.[3]\n\nThat said, we don\u0027t necessarily have to do things the lottiecap way. If you prefer to keep it simple and use the Chromium version bundled with Puppeteer, we can absolutely do that.\n\nPlease let me know what you prefer.\n\n[1] https://github.com/google/skia/blob/4afe94c940c44bc7ec5c81b9416b73596437e72a/infra/lottiecap/docker/lottie-web-puppeteer/Dockerfile#L21\n[2] https://github.com/google/skia/blob/4afe94c940c44bc7ec5c81b9416b73596437e72a/infra/lottiecap/docker/lottie-web-puppeteer/Dockerfile#L19\n[3] https://github.com/google/skia/blob/67d43fe581873e62ff8daef2bb7fd72645e91fa5/tools/lottiecap/lottiecap.js#L138",
      "parentUuid": "ee6180e5_8d1c5268",
      "revId": "e67fab2f2e75fd3a4f72c242d5ccd0be34190529",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
